# ACT ONE — THE GROUND

[[ The cage. ~25 min, ending on the Doorway of No Return. Birdy's small, erasing life; the love that can't reach him; his one secret aliveness; the unbearable tenderness of a man saying goodbye without anyone seeing it. ]]

## 1. COLD OPEN / SKY TEASE

= Birdy (cockpit, gold hour) and Bishop (radio). Birdy wants one more minute of sky and puts off landing with a joke that lands like a goodbye. Hard cut before we understand it. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 2. THE RAMP

= Birdy and Dez in the rain. Dez wants him to march in and demand his raise; Birdy takes the smaller hit and waves a jet out into a sky he never gets to fly. (want/wall/turn present.) TO WRITE — new bar.

## 3. HOME

= Maya wants one true sentence; gets "I'm fine"; the gap widens. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 4. THE SIMULATOR

= Maya wants into the one room where he's still alive; glimpses the man she married fly for a few seconds before the shutter drops. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 5. THE KINDNESS

= Birdy presses cash he can't spare on Dez; Dez, taking it, finally senses something is wrong. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 6. THE DISCOVERY

= Maya, having found the pills, tries to say it and ask him to stay — and the words die; she says goodnight and hates herself. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 7. THE LAST ORDINARY MORNING

= Birdy gives Maya a perfect day she won't recognize as goodbye; she almost holds him here; the weight wins. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 8. THE EVE

= Birdy sends Dez home with a warm lie and turns to the empty plane in the dark. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 9. DOORWAY OF NO RETURN — THE HIJACK

= The tower catches the rogue taxi; Bishop orders him to stop; Birdy lifts off, airborne and alone. Act 1 break. TO WRITE — new bar.

# ACT TWO — THE SKY

[[ The hour. ~50 min. The world erupts; Bishop insists on reaching the man, not the threat; the terror loosens into wonder; the sky peak; then the honest reckoning with what landing costs. ]]

## 10. FIRST CONTACT

= Bishop refuses to bark and talks to him like a person; Birdy, startled, answers. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 11. THE FREEDOM BEGINS

= Birdy asks for the orca; Bishop breaks a rule and gives him the heading; the beauty starts to loosen something he thought was dead. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 12. THE ESCALATION

= Maya is brought to the tower and begs for the radio; Bishop keys her in; "I left the porch light on." The stakes turn unbearable. TO WRITE — new bar.

## 13. THE ROLL — THE SKY PEAK

INT./EXT. TURBOPROP COCKPIT - GOLDEN HOUR (AIRBORNE)

The plane is small in a wide gold sky. Below, the city is hazed and far down.

BIRDY sits at the controls. Headset on. His face is slack. His hands move on instinct, no more.

The fuel gauge sits in the low quarter.

A burst of static.

BISHOP (V.O.)
Still with me?

Birdy wets his lips. Takes a second to find his voice.

BIRDY
Yeah.

He looks out the side window.

The sun sits low on the horizon. It fills the cockpit. The light is on his hands, his knees, the dash.

Far below, the city is coming on. One light, then more, then a whole grid of them in the blue.

Birdy watches the lights come up.

He pulls back on the yoke. The nose lifts. The plane climbs.

The haze drops away under him. Above it, the gold is clean.

Birdy's eyes are wet now. He keeps climbing.

His hand goes to the yoke. He banks left a little. Levels. Banks again. He watches the wing dip and come back.

He holds the yoke. He doesn't move.

Then he turns it all the way over.

The horizon rolls. Gold swings up the windshield, across the top, down the other side. The city wheels overhead and comes back under him.

The plane comes level.

Birdy lets out a breath that turns into a laugh. A short one, surprised.

Then another. It keeps coming and he can't stop it, and it isn't only laughing anymore. His face is wet, his shoulders are going.

He laughs and cries at the same time, both hands over his mouth, the yoke loose between his knees.

BISHOP (V.O.)
You okay up there?

Birdy nods. Then remembers to speak.

BIRDY
Yeah. Yeah. I'm —

He stops. Wipes his face with the back of his wrist.

BIRDY (CONT'D)
Okay.

He sits a moment. Breathing. The gold is going to dusk on his face.

He puts his hands back on the controls.

He banks the nose around, toward the field, toward the lights coming up below.

The sun drops under the horizon. The gold leaves his face.

> CUT TO:

## 14. THE HONEST DEAL — THE DA NEGOTIATION

INT./EXT. TURBOPROP COCKPIT - DUSK (AIRBORNE)

The gold has gone orange in the windscreen. BIRDY, mid-forties, ramp coveralls, one hand loose on the yoke. Out the left window, a fighter jet sits off the wingtip, close enough to see the pilot's helmet.

The fuel gauge needle rests low. Birdy taps the glass with one finger. Watches the needle not move.

INTERCUT - TOWER CAB

BISHOP at the console, headset on, eyes on the radar. The slow blip crawls between two fast ones. REYES stands beside him, a hand already out for the spare mic. Bishop looks at her. Holds the mic a second before he gives it over.

REYES
(into mic)
Birdy. My name's Reyes. I work for the county.

BIRDY
County.

REYES
I'm going to make this simple. You bring it down now, right now, and there's no charges. Clean. You walk.

Birdy looks out at the jet. The pilot looks back.

BIRDY
You can do that.

REYES
I'm telling you I can.

A long beat. Birdy lets out a breath through his nose. Almost a laugh.

BIRDY
No.

REYES
No what.

BIRDY
I'm not — I'm slow, but I'm not stupid.

Reyes' jaw tightens. Bishop keeps his eyes on the radar.

BIRDY (CONT'D)
I took an airplane. I know I did something.

REYES
Birdy —

BIRDY
Don't. Please.

Birdy's thumb moves on the yoke.

BIRDY (CONT'D)
Just tell me the real one. What it actually is.

Reyes lowers the mic. Looks at Bishop. Bishop doesn't help her. She brings it back up.

REYES
Okay.

She sets her feet.

REYES (CONT'D)
You're going to be charged. That's true no matter what I say up here. I can't make that go away and I'm not going to sit here and pretend.

INTERCUT - COCKPIT

Birdy goes still. Listening.

REYES (V.O.)
So here's what's real. You put this thing down. Nobody on the ground gets hurt.

BIRDY
Nobody. I picked the airplane that was empty. I checked.

REYES (V.O.)
I believe you.

INTERCUT - TOWER CAB

REYES
You land it clean, and I go in front of a judge myself. I argue it. Suspended sentence. You'd answer for it. There'd be rules, people checking on you. But not a cell. That's the one I'd fight for.

A pause on the line. The blip holds.

REYES (CONT'D)
I can't promise the judge. I can promise I'll be standing there.

INTERCUT - COCKPIT

Birdy is quiet a moment. He looks at the orange going out of the glass.

BIRDY
Rules.

REYES (V.O.)
Yeah.

BIRDY
Somebody checking on me.

REYES (V.O.)
Probably for a while.

Birdy nods to himself. Wipes his nose with the back of his hand.

BIRDY
That's the part that scares me. More than the —
(he stops)
The rest of it.

REYES (V.O.)
I know.

BIRDY
You don't, but. Thanks.

He puts his other hand on the yoke. Both hands now.

BISHOP (V.O.)
Birdy. You still with me?

BIRDY
Yeah, Bishop.

BISHOP (V.O.)
That offer she made. That's a true one.

Birdy watches the fighter pilot off his wing. Lifts two fingers off the yoke. The pilot, after a moment, lifts a gloved hand back.

BIRDY
Okay.

REYES (V.O.)
Okay what.

BIRDY
Tell me where you want me to put it.

He levels the wings. The needle sits low and steady. Out the windscreen, far off, the city starts to come on, light by light.

> CUT TO:

